SIMPLE: pollute
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pollute
<hw>Pol*lute"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Polluted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Polluting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>pollutus</ets>, p. p.
of <ets>polluere</ets> to defile, to pollute, from a prep. appearing
only in comp. + <ets>luere</ets> to wash. See <er>Position</er>,
<er>Lave</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make foul, impure, or unclean;
to defile; to taint; to soil; to desecrate; -- used of physical or moral
defilement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The land was <qex>polluted</qex> with blood.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. cvi.
38</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wickedness . . . hath <qex>polluted</qex> the whole earth.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Esd. xv. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To violate sexually; to debauch; to
dishonor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Jewish Law)</fld> <def>To render ceremonially
unclean; to disqualify or unfit for sacred use or service, or for social
intercourse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither shall ye <qex>pollute</qex> the holy things of the
children of Israel, lest ye die.</q> <rj><qau>Num. xviii.
32.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They have <qex>polluted</qex> themselves with blood.</q>
<rj><qau>Lam. iv. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To defile; soil; contaminate; corrupt; taint;
vitiate; debauch; dishonor; ravish.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pollute</ent>⟦br⟧

